---

<KnowledgeHubLayout
  title="Single Phase vs Three Phase Electrical Load | Electrical Knowledge Hub"
  description="Learn the difference between single-phase and three-phase electrical load — when to use each, formulas, and practical examples for homes and businesses."
  keywords="single phase vs three phase, three phase load calculation, single phase load calculation, single phase three phase difference, three phase power for home"
  breadcrumb={[
    { label: 'Home', href: '/' },
    { label: 'Knowledge Hub', href: '/knowledge-hub' },
    { label: 'Load Calculation', href: '/knowledge-hub/load-calculation' },
    { label: 'Single Phase vs Three Phase' },
  ]}
  toc={toc}
  readingTime={6}
  datePublished="2025-06-18"
  dateModified="2025-06-18"
  schemaGraph={schemaGraph}
  relatedArticles={relatedArticles}
  clusterSlug="load-calculation"
  clusterTitle="Load Calculation"
>

  <!-- ─── Quick Answer ─── -->
  <QuickAnswerBox id="quick-answer">
    <p>
      <strong>Single-phase power (230V)</strong> is used for most Indian homes with loads up to 10 kW.
      <strong>Three-phase power (415V line-to-line)</strong> is required when your total load exceeds 10 kW,
      or when you run heavy equipment like industrial motors, lifts, or multiple large air conditioners.
      The key formula difference: single-phase uses <code>P = V × I × PF</code>, while three-phase uses
      <code>P = √3 × V × I × PF</code>.
    </p>
  </QuickAnswerBox>

  <!-- ─── Visual Explanation ─── -->
  <h2 id="visual-explanation">Single Phase vs Three Phase — Side-by-Side Comparison</h2>

  <p>
    Think of electrical phases like lanes on a highway. A single-phase connection is a one-lane road —
    adequate for a family car (your home's typical appliances). A three-phase connection is a three-lane
    highway — essential when you need to move heavy machinery or large industrial loads simultaneously
    and smoothly.
  </p>

  <p>
    In India, the standard single-phase supply is <strong>230V between the live wire and neutral</strong>.
    Three-phase supply delivers <strong>415V between any two live wires</strong> (line-to-line) and 230V
    between each live wire and neutral (line-to-neutral). This is why three-phase connections can power
    heavier loads — the voltage and the simultaneous three-wave delivery provide much higher capacity.
  </p>

  <div class="table-wrap">
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Feature</th>
          <th>Single Phase</th>
          <th>Three Phase</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Supply Voltage</strong></td>
          <td>230V (Line to Neutral)</td>
          <td>415V (Line to Line) / 230V (L-N)</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Number of Phases</strong></td>
          <td>1</td>
          <td>3</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Power Formula</strong></td>
          <td><code>P = V × I × PF</code></td>
          <td><code>P = √3 × V × I × PF</code></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Typical Max Load</strong></td>
          <td>Up to 10 kW</td>
          <td>10 kW and above (no practical limit)</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Wiring</strong></td>
          <td>2 wires (1 Live + 1 Neutral)</td>
          <td>4 wires (3 Live + 1 Neutral)</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Common Use Cases</strong></td>
          <td>Homes, small shops, small offices</td>
          <td>Industry, workshops, large buildings, malls</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>MCB / Main Switch</strong></td>
          <td>Single-pole or DP MCB</td>
          <td>TP (3-pole) or TPN (4-pole) MCB/MCCB</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Efficiency</strong></td>
          <td>Good for light loads</td>
          <td>Higher efficiency for heavy loads</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Motor Starting</strong></td>
          <td>Not suitable for large motors</td>
          <td>Ideal for 3-phase induction motors</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Typical India Connection</strong></td>
          <td>Standard residential</td>
          <td>Industrial / commercial sanction</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <!-- ─── Step-by-Step ─── -->
  <h2 id="step-by-step">Step-by-Step: How to Calculate Load for Each Type</h2>

  <p>
    The load calculation process is similar for both — you list all appliances, find their wattage,
    and add them up. The key difference is which formula you use to find the current (amperes) flowing
    through the supply cables.
  </p>

  <h3 id="single-phase-steps">Single-Phase Load Calculation</h3>

  <div class="step-card">
    <div class="step-number">1</div>
    <div>
      <strong>List all appliances and their wattage</strong>
      <p>
        Write down every appliance in your home with its rated wattage. You can find this on the product
        label, in the user manual, or use our <a href="/knowledge-hub/load-calculation/electrical-load-chart-for-home-appliances" data-astro-prefetch="hover">appliance wattage chart</a>.
        Example: 4 ceiling fans × 75W, 8 LED bulbs × 10W, 1 AC × 1600W, 1 fridge × 200W.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="step-card">
    <div class="step-number">2</div>
    <div>
      <strong>Sum the total watts</strong>
      <p>
        Add all wattages together: (4×75) + (8×10) + 1600 + 200 = 300 + 80 + 1600 + 200 = <strong>2,180 W</strong>.
        Convert to kilowatts: 2,180 ÷ 1,000 = <strong>2.18 kW</strong> connected load.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="step-card">
    <div class="step-number">3</div>
    <div>
      <strong>Apply the single-phase current formula</strong>
      <p>
        Use <code>I = P ÷ (V × PF)</code> where V = 230V and PF (power factor) ≈ 0.85 for a typical home.
        So: I = 2,180 ÷ (230 × 0.85) = 2,180 ÷ 195.5 ≈ <strong>11.1 Amperes</strong>.
        This tells you the main MCB rating needed (round up to the next standard size — 16A).
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="step-card">
    <div class="step-number">4</div>
    <div>
      <strong>Apply a demand factor (diversity factor)</strong>
      <p>
        Not all appliances run simultaneously. A demand factor of 0.7–0.8 is realistic for homes.
        Maximum demand = 2,180 × 0.75 ≈ <strong>1,635 W</strong> (1.6 kW peak load).
        This helps you right-size your main switch and cable instead of over-specifying.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h3 id="three-phase-steps">Three-Phase Load Calculation</h3>

  <div class="step-card">
    <div class="step-number">1</div>
    <div>
      <strong>List and sum all load watts — same as single phase</strong>
      <p>
        Example workshop: 5 × 1.5 Ton AC (1,600W each) + 10 × 150W industrial lights + 1 × 5 HP motor
        (3,730W) = 8,000 + 1,500 + 3,730 = <strong>13,230 W (13.23 kW)</strong>.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="step-card">
    <div class="step-number">2</div>
    <div>
      <strong>Apply the three-phase current formula</strong>
      <p>
        Use <code>I = P ÷ (√3 × V_LL × PF)</code> where V_LL = 415V (line-to-line) and PF ≈ 0.85.
        √3 ≈ 1.732. So: I = 13,230 ÷ (1.732 × 415 × 0.85) = 13,230 ÷ 611 ≈ <strong>21.6 Amperes per phase</strong>.
        Choose a 25A TPN MCB for the main switch.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="step-card">
    <div class="step-number">3</div>
    <div>
      <strong>Balance the load across all three phases</strong>
      <p>
        Distribute appliances so each phase carries roughly equal load (within 10% of each other).
        Unbalanced phases cause voltage fluctuations, neutral current overloading, and equipment damage.
        Assign: Phase A = 3 ACs + 5 lights = 5,550W; Phase B = 2 ACs + 5 lights = 3,950W; Phase C = motor + lights = 4,480W.
        This is close enough — adjust further if needed.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="step-card">
    <div class="step-number">4</div>
    <div>
      <strong>Verify and select cable size</strong>
      <p>
        For 21.6A per phase, a 4 sq.mm copper cable (rated ~27A) is appropriate. Always add a 20%
        safety margin and check voltage drop does not exceed 5% over the cable run length.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ─── Real Example ─── -->
  <h2 id="real-example">Real Example: Home vs Workshop</h2>

  <div class="example-box">
    <p class="example-label">Example A — 2 AC Home (Single Phase)</p>
    <p>
      A typical 2BHK home in India with 2 split ACs (1.5 Ton each), 4 ceiling fans, 8 LED bulbs,
      1 refrigerator, 1 TV, and 1 washing machine.
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>2 × 1.5 Ton AC @ 1,600W = <strong>3,200W</strong></li>
      <li>4 × Ceiling Fan @ 75W = <strong>300W</strong></li>
      <li>8 × LED Bulb @ 10W = <strong>80W</strong></li>
      <li>1 × Refrigerator @ 200W = <strong>200W</strong></li>
      <li>1 × TV (40") @ 90W = <strong>90W</strong></li>
      <li>1 × Washing Machine @ 500W = <strong>500W</strong></li>
    </ul>
    <p><strong>Total Connected Load:</strong> 4,370W = <strong>4.37 kW</strong></p>
    <p>
      <strong>Single-phase current:</strong> I = 4,370 ÷ (230 × 0.85) ≈ <strong>22.4A</strong>
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Verdict:</strong> Well within single-phase range. A <strong>32A single-phase connection</strong>
      with a 32A DP MCB is adequate. No need for three-phase.
    </p>
  </div>

  <div class="example-box">
    <p class="example-label">Example B — Small Workshop (Three Phase Required)</p>
    <p>
      A small manufacturing workshop with 3 × 2 Ton ACs, 10 × 150W industrial tube lights,
      1 × 7.5 HP (5.6 kW) single motor, and 2 × 1 HP motors.
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>3 × 2 Ton AC @ 2,000W = <strong>6,000W</strong></li>
      <li>10 × Industrial Light @ 150W = <strong>1,500W</strong></li>
      <li>1 × 7.5 HP Motor @ 5,600W = <strong>5,600W</strong></li>
      <li>2 × 1 HP Motor @ 750W = <strong>1,500W</strong></li>
    </ul>
    <p><strong>Total Connected Load:</strong> 14,600W = <strong>14.6 kW</strong></p>
    <p>
      <strong>Three-phase current:</strong> I = 14,600 ÷ (1.732 × 415 × 0.85) ≈ <strong>23.9A per phase</strong>
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Verdict:</strong> Load exceeds 10 kW AND includes an induction motor — <strong>three-phase is mandatory</strong>.
      Apply for a 3-phase 25A connection. Use a 32A TPN MCB for main switch.
    </p>
  </div>

  <!-- ─── Reference Table ─── -->
  <h2 id="reference-table">Quick Reference Table</h2>

  <div class="table-wrap">
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Parameter</th>
          <th>Single Phase</th>
          <th>Three Phase</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td>Phase Voltage (L-N)</td>
          <td>230V</td>
          <td>230V</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Line Voltage (L-L)</td>
          <td>230V (only 1 phase)</td>
          <td>415V</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Power Formula</td>
          <td><code>P = V × I × PF</code></td>
          <td><code>P = √3 × VLL × I × PF</code></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Current Formula</td>
          <td><code>I = P ÷ (V × PF)</code></td>
          <td><code>I = P ÷ (√3 × VLL × PF)</code></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>√3 Factor</td>
          <td>Not applicable</td>
          <td>1.732</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Typical Applications</td>
          <td>Home, small shop, office &lt;10 kW</td>
          <td>Industry, 3-phase motors, large buildings</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Main MCB Type</td>
          <td>SP or DP (1 or 2 pole)</td>
          <td>TP (3-pole) or TPN (4-pole)</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Neutral Wire</td>
          <td>1 neutral wire required</td>
          <td>1 shared neutral wire</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Phase Balancing</td>
          <td>Not required</td>
          <td>Required — keep within 10% per phase</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Motor Starting</td>
          <td>Capacitor-start motors only</td>
          <td>3-phase induction motors directly</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Load Limit (India sanction)</td>
          <td>Up to 10 kW typically</td>
          <td>Above 10 kW (industrial sanction)</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <!-- ─── Common Mistakes ─── -->
  <h2 id="common-mistakes">Common Mistakes to Avoid</h2>

  <div class="mistake-card">
    <span style="font-size:1.25rem;flex-shrink:0;" aria-hidden="true">⚠️</span>
    <div>
      <strong>Assuming three-phase is always better</strong>
      <p style="margin:0.25rem 0 0;font-size:0.875rem;color:var(--text-muted);">
        Three-phase is more efficient for large loads and motors, but for a regular 2–3 BHK home
        it adds unnecessary complexity and cost. Your discom may also charge higher fixed charges
        for commercial/three-phase connections. Stick to single-phase unless your load genuinely
        exceeds 10 kW.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="mistake-card">
    <span style="font-size:1.25rem;flex-shrink:0;" aria-hidden="true">⚠️</span>
    <div>
      <strong>Using the wrong current formula</strong>
      <p style="margin:0.25rem 0 0;font-size:0.875rem;color:var(--text-muted);">
        Using <code>I = P ÷ V</code> without the power factor gives you an optimistic (too low) current value.
        Always include PF (typically 0.8–0.9 for home appliances). For three-phase, forgetting the
        √3 (1.732) multiplier is a serious error that leads to undersized cables and MCBs.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="mistake-card">
    <span style="font-size:1.25rem;flex-shrink:0;" aria-hidden="true">⚠️</span>
    <div>
      <strong>Poor phase balancing on three-phase systems</strong>
      <p style="margin:0.25rem 0 0;font-size:0.875rem;color:var(--text-muted);">
        Dumping all your heavy loads onto Phase A while Phases B and C carry almost nothing causes
        the neutral wire to carry excess current, leads to voltage imbalance, and can damage
        equipment with sensitive electronics. Always distribute loads as evenly as possible across
        all three phases.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="mistake-card">
    <span style="font-size:1.25rem;flex-shrink:0;" aria-hidden="true">⚠️</span>
    <div>
      <strong>Confusing line voltage with phase voltage</strong>
      <p style="margin:0.25rem 0 0;font-size:0.875rem;color:var(--text-muted);">
        In a three-phase system, the voltage between two live wires (line-to-line) is 415V,
        but the voltage between a live wire and neutral (line-to-neutral) is 230V. Using 415V
        in your formula when you mean L-N voltage — or vice versa — produces completely wrong
        current calculations.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="mistake-card">
    <span style="font-size:1.25rem;flex-shrink:0;" aria-hidden="true">⚠️</span>
    <div>
      <strong>Ignoring motor starting current</strong>
      <p style="margin:0.25rem 0 0;font-size:0.875rem;color:var(--text-muted);">
        Three-phase induction motors draw 5–7× their full-load current during startup (inrush current).
        A 7.5 HP motor running at 15A continuously might pull 90–100A for a second or two on start.
        Your MCB and cable must be rated to handle this — use a motor-rated MCB or a star-delta starter
        for motors above 5 HP.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ─── CTA ─── -->
  <KnowledgeHubCTA id="use-the-calculator" />

  <!-- ─── FAQs ─── -->
  <h2 id="faqs">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

  <div class="kh-faq">
    <details>
      <summary>
        Can I convert my home from single-phase to three-phase?
        <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" viewBox="0 0 16 16" fill="currentColor" class="faq-chevron w-4 h-4"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M4.22 6.22a.75.75 0 0 1 1.06 0L8 8.94l2.72-2.72a.75.75 0 1 1 1.06 1.06l-3.25 3.25a.75.75 0 0 1-1.06 0L4.22 7.28a.75.75 0 0 1 0-1.06Z" clip-rule="evenodd" /></svg>
      </summary>
      <div class="faq-body">
        Yes, but it requires an application to your local electricity distribution company (DISCOM)
        for a revised sanction load. An electrician will need to upgrade your main switchboard to a
        TPN (four-pole) board, and the DISCOM will install a three-phase energy meter. This is typically
        done when your sanctioned load exceeds 10 kW. The internal wiring of existing single-phase
        circuits does not need to change — you simply add new three-phase circuits for heavy loads.
      </div>
    </details>

    <details>
      <summary>
        Is three-phase power cheaper than single phase in India?
        <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" viewBox="0 0 16 16" fill="currentColor" class="faq-chevron w-4 h-4"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M4.22 6.22a.75.75 0 0 1 1.06 0L8 8.94l2.72-2.72a.75.75 0 1 1 1.06 1.06l-3.25 3.25a.75.75 0 0 1-1.06 0L4.22 7.28a.75.75 0 0 1 0-1.06Z" clip-rule="evenodd" /></svg>
      </summary>
      <div class="faq-body">
        Not necessarily cheaper per unit. However, for large motor loads, three-phase is more
        <em>energy-efficient</em> because three-phase induction motors have higher power factors (0.85–0.95)
        and better efficiency than single-phase alternatives. In India, three-phase connections may fall
        under commercial/LT industrial tariff categories, which often have higher fixed demand charges
        but lower per-unit costs at high consumption volumes. Check your state DISCOM's tariff order.
      </div>
    </details>

    <details>
      <summary>
        What happens if I run a three-phase appliance on single-phase supply?
        <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" viewBox="0 0 16 16" fill="currentColor" class="faq-chevron w-4 h-4"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M4.22 6.22a.75.75 0 0 1 1.06 0L8 8.94l2.72-2.72a.75.75 0 1 1 1.06 1.06l-3.25 3.25a.75.75 0 0 1-1.06 0L4.22 7.28a.75.75 0 0 1 0-1.06Z" clip-rule="evenodd" /></svg>
      </summary>
      <div class="faq-body">
        A three-phase appliance (like a three-phase induction motor) will not start on single-phase
        supply. If it manages to start (e.g., under light load with a capacitor trick), it will overheat,
        vibrate excessively, and burn out quickly. Never run three-phase equipment on single-phase power
        without a proper phase converter — and even then, performance is degraded significantly.
      </div>
    </details>

    <details>
      <summary>
        What is meant by a "balanced three-phase load"?
        <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" viewBox="0 0 16 16" fill="currentColor" class="faq-chevron w-4 h-4"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M4.22 6.22a.75.75 0 0 1 1.06 0L8 8.94l2.72-2.72a.75.75 0 1 1 1.06 1.06l-3.25 3.25a.75.75 0 0 1-1.06 0L4.22 7.28a.75.75 0 0 1 0-1.06Z" clip-rule="evenodd" /></svg>
      </summary>
      <div class="faq-body">
        A balanced three-phase load means all three phases (R, Y, B) carry equal current and power.
        In a perfectly balanced system, the neutral current is zero, voltage across all phases is
        equal (230V each), and the system operates at peak efficiency. In practice, residential
        three-phase boards are "balanced" when each phase carries within 10% of the others.
        Most three-phase motors present a naturally balanced load.
      </div>
    </details>

    <details>
      <summary>
        What is the √3 (root 3) factor in three-phase calculations?
        <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" viewBox="0 0 16 16" fill="currentColor" class="faq-chevron w-4 h-4"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M4.22 6.22a.75.75 0 0 1 1.06 0L8 8.94l2.72-2.72a.75.75 0 1 1 1.06 1.06l-3.25 3.25a.75.75 0 0 1-1.06 0L4.22 7.28a.75.75 0 0 1 0-1.06Z" clip-rule="evenodd" /></svg>
      </summary>
      <div class="faq-body">
        The √3 factor (approximately 1.732) arises from the geometry of three sine waves separated by
        120° from each other. When you measure the voltage between two live phases (line-to-line),
        it is √3 times the phase-to-neutral voltage. So: 230V × 1.732 = 415V line-to-line. This same
        factor appears in the three-phase power formula: <code>P = √3 × V_LL × I × PF</code>.
      </div>
    </details>

    <details>
      <summary>
        Can I run my home inverter on three-phase supply?
        <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" viewBox="0 0 16 16" fill="currentColor" class="faq-chevron w-4 h-4"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M4.22 6.22a.75.75 0 0 1 1.06 0L8 8.94l2.72-2.72a.75.75 0 1 1 1.06 1.06l-3.25 3.25a.75.75 0 0 1-1.06 0L4.22 7.28a.75.75 0 0 1 0-1.06Z" clip-rule="evenodd" /></svg>
      </summary>
      <div class="faq-body">
        Most residential inverters (Luminous, Microtek, Exide) are single-phase devices — they take
        one live wire (230V) input and output single-phase 230V during a power cut. If your home has
        a three-phase connection, the inverter simply connects to one of the three phases. For whole-home
        backup on three-phase, you need a three-phase inverter or a separate inverter per phase, which
        is significantly more expensive. Industrial three-phase UPS/inverters are available for
        commercial applications.
      </div>
    </details>
  </div>

